        {
          "text": "This page presents a comparison between D.W. Griffith’s "
        },
        {
          "text": "The Lonely Villa",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " and Lois Weber’s "
        },
        {
          "text": "Suspense",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". While each film holds its own artistic and historical value, it is in the side-by-side viewing that their contrasts—and Weber’s innovations—truly emerge. By reimagining a similar plot, "
        },
        {
          "text": "Suspense",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " elevates the material through dynamic camera angles, a departure from static proscenium-style long shots, and a range of experimental techniques that push the boundaries of early cinematic language"
        }
      ]
